resilience is inherently tied to macroeconomic fundamentals, as systemic stability cannot exist in isolation from real-economy dynamics.2
Thus, AI may reshape the multiple dimensions of financial resilience, which may directly affect the stability of both the real
economy and the financial system (Zhong et al. 2024).
Energy, the lifeblood of economic activity, connects to financial resilience through its implications for pricing mechanisms, global
supply chains, and asset valuation (Guo et al. 2025). Geopolitical tensions, transition risks inherent in the shift from fossil fuels to
renewables, and extreme weather events frequently induce sharp volatility in energy prices. This volatility disrupts the cash flow of
energy-intensive enterprises, elevates nonperforming loans in energy sector financing, and amplifies fluctuations in energy derivatives
markets (Zhang et al. 2023; Qin et al. 2025). Global economic conditions, meanwhile, provide the macroeconomic backdrop for
financial activities as key indicators, including global GDP growth, inflation rates, and cross-border capital flows, directly influencing
corporate profitability, household solvency, and financial asset pricing (Hong et al. 2024; Liang et al. 2025). For instance, global
economic recessions typically trigger a surge in corporate defaults, a sharp decline in asset prices, and liquidity tightening, thereby
testing the financial system’s shock absorption capacity; conversely, robust economic expansion improves the credit quality of market
participants and reinforces the resilience of financial institutions (Dees 2016). Worldwide industrial production, the core of the real
economy, serves as a transmission channel between the real economy and financial resilience (Duan et al. 2022). Fluctuations in
industrial output driven by supply chain disruptions, shifts in global demand, and other factors directly affect the revenue and
debt-servicing capacity of manufacturing enterprises, which are key borrowers in the financial system.
To empirically examine the dynamic interplay between AI and the three dimensions of financial resilience outlined above, this
study applies widely used indices, paired with an approach tailored to capturing time-varying relationships. The development of AI is
proxied by the S&P’s Kensho New Economy RAIC Index, a benchmark specifically designed to track the performance of companies at
the forefront of AI, robotics, automation, and connected car technologies. This index is favoured for its comprehensive coverage of
firms driving AI innovation across sectors, making it a robust indicator of AI development trends (Zhong et al. 2024; Yu et al. 2025).
For the three dimensions of financial resilience, we adopt the following indicators. The Global Energy-Related Uncertainty Index (ERU)
quantifies uncertainty stemming from energy markets, including price volatility, supply disruptions, and policy shifts, directly
reflecting energy-related resilience (Dang et al. 2023; Li et al. 2025). The Global Economic Condition Index (GECON), a composite
measure that integrates global GDP growth, inflation, and capital flow dynamics to gauge macroeconomic stability, serving as a proxy
for economic condition-related resilience (Baumeister and Hamilton 2019). The Worldwide Industrial Production Index (WIP) tracks
output trends in manufacturing, mining, and utilities worldwide, capturing industrial production-related resilience (Baumeister et al.
2022). To elucidate the time-varying causal links between AI and these resilience indicators, this study employs the time-varying
Granger causality test. Unlike the traditional Granger causality test, which assumes that the causal relationship is constant over
time, this method estimates the parameters of different subsamples by implementing window changes in the window algorithm,
thereby constructing a time-varying test statistic that can detect the evolution direction of the causal relationship within the sample
period (Shi et al. 2020). This flexibility is critical given the rapidly evolving nature of AI technology and the dynamic shocks (such as
geopolitical events and economic crises) that characterize energy, economic, and industrial systems, aligning precisely with the study’s
focus on time-varying correlations.
2. Bidirectional static and dynamic Granger test
In time series analysis, the determination of causal relationships often relies on predictability, an idea proposed by the Granger
causality test (Granger 1969). This test applies the Vector Autoregression (VAR) model to a set of related variables to determine causal
relationships, but it has significant limitations—causal relationships may be inconsistent across different time periods, and it cannot
capture the dynamic change characteristics of time series (Ren et al. 2024; Hong et al. 2025). To address the static limitations of
traditional methods, Shi et al. (2020) reexamined the concept of Granger causality, introduced the time-varying characteristic and
proposed a time-varying Granger causality test framework. In this study, the causality test process proposed by Shi et al. (2020) is
adopted.
