3. Data and sources
3.1. Data information
The core variables selected for this study are all sourced from authoritative platforms to ensure the reliability and traceability of the
indicators. The specific sources of each variable are as follows.
The S&P Kensho New Economy RAIC Index is an equity index compiled by the S&P Dow Jones Indices. Its core objective is to
provide a comprehensive representation of the nine front-line industry boards that balance weight, equipment, people, artificial intelligence,
and accounting. This is an indirect selection of the index, which explains why the new Kensho index series consists of nine
subindexes in the middle, including the RAIC and previous technology areas. To comprehensively cover artificial intelligence across
various industries, many studies have used this index to capture the development of AI (Zhong et al. 2024; Yu et al. 2025). This index is
sourced from the S&P Dow Jones Indices website.
The financial resilience referred to in this paper is not simply the soundness of financial institutions but rather a systemic capability
arising from the interaction of the macroeconomic environment, the real economy, and the financial system.
(1) The Energy-related Uncertainty Indicator (ERU). Energy price fluctuations are transmitted across the entire industrial chain
through production costs, triggering macroeconomic fluctuations (Punzi 2019). In addition, the increase in energy-related
uncertainty directly leads to an increase in the volatility of financial asset prices and the accumulation of credit risk (Zhang
2018). The ERU is not simply macroeconomic pressure, and its correlation with financial resilience has been confirmed by many
studies (Szczygielski et al. 2025; Yang and Fu 2025). This index is sourced from the official Economic Policy Uncertainty
website.
(2) The Global Economic Conditions Indicator (GECON). The stability of the financial system cannot exist independently of
macroeconomic fundamentals (Mishkin 2000). The sustainable growth and low volatility of the global economy support
financial resilience. The GECON measures the overall stability and sustainability of the macroeconomy (Baumeister et al. 2022)
and therefore can be used as a proxy indicator for financial resilience.
(3) World Industrial Production Indicators (WIP). Industrial production is a key link between the real economy and the financial
system, and its resilience directly affects the asset quality and functional maintenance capacity of the financial system (Duan
et al. 2022). The GECON and WIP are directly obtained from Christiane Baumeister’s personal website.
Since the original data for AI and ERU are daily, whereas the GECON and WIP data are monthly, the daily data of the first two
variables are processed into monthly mean values to ensure consistency in variable frequency. Using the calendar month as the time
unit, we calculate the arithmetic mean of the daily AI and ERU data within each month and convert these means into monthly data.
This ensures that all the variables are measured on a monthly basis for subsequent analysis. The research sample period is ultimately
set from January 2014 to November 2023, primarily on the basis of data availability.
