3.2. Stationarity test
To test the stationarity of the time series, this paper uses two unit-root tests, namely, the ADF and KPSS. In Table 1, the ADF
statistics for the variables AI, ERU, GECON, and WIP have p-values of 0.001. The null hypothesis of a unit root is rejected, indicating a
stationary series. In the KPSS test, the KPSS statistics for AI, ERU, GECON, and WIP have p values greater than 0.01. Therefore, the null
hypothesis of stationarity cannot be rejected. On the basis of both tests, all four variables are stationary time series and can be directly
used in subsequent econometric analysis.
3.3. Descriptive statistics
Table 2 reports the descriptive statistics of the variables, which can be summarized from the perspectives of central tendency,
dispersion, and distribution pattern. First, the mean value of the AI is 1.181, and that of the WIP is 0.189, both showing slightly positive
trends. The mean values of ERU and GECON are − 0.002 and − 0.001, respectively, which are close to zero, indicating that the values of
these four variables generally fluctuate around zero. Second, the standard deviation of the AI is 13.647, which is significantly greater
than those of ERU, GECON, and WIP, indicating that the AI is significantly more dispersed, whereas ERU and GECON are relatively less
dispersed. Third, the skewness of the AI is − 0.203, which is nearly symmetrical, whereas that of the ERU is 0.393, which is slightly
right skewed. The skewness of GECON is 2.273, which is significantly right skewed, and the skewness of WIP is − 3.635, which is left
skewed. In terms of kurtosis, AI and ERU exhibit peak distributions, whereas GECON and WIP exhibit extremely peaked distributions.
These findings indicate that the distributions of GECON and WIP deviate significantly from a normal distribution and exhibit distinct
asymmetric peak characteristics. In summary, each variable has different characteristics in terms of central tendency, dispersion, and
distribution morphology.
