4. Bidirectional causality analyses
In our testing methodology, we refer to the study by Shi et al. (2020) and Ren et al. (2023), who assumed a minimum subsample
size of δ0 =72 and controlled the recursively expanding window size τ =12.
4.1. Static analyses
To analyse Granger causality between variables, Wald test statistics are compared with critical values (CVs) at the 90 %, 95 %, and
99 % significance levels. We present the results in Table 3. The results showed that AI can Granger-cause ERU, GECON and WIP at the 1
% significance level. ERU does not Granger-cause AI, GECON, or WIP. GECON can significantly Granger-cause AI, ERU, and WIP at the
1 % significance level. WIP does not Granger-cause AI but does Granger-cause ERU at the 5 % significance level and GECON at the 1 %
significance level. Overall, AI, GECON, and WIP exhibit significant Granger causality in multiple directions, whereas the influences of
ERU on the other variables are nonsignificant. Furthermore, AI and GECON and GECON and WIP form bidirectional causal loops,
demonstrating mutual influence and feedback mechanisms. However, AI and ERU/WIP exhibit unidirectional causal relationships,
indicating unidirectional transmission of the impact of AI on ERU or WIP. Furthermore, GECON and WIP also have unidirectional
effects on ERU, implying that the EUR is a risk receiver. Therefore, we further explore the time-varying transmission of these risks.
4.2. Dynamic analyses
The results of the time-varying Granger causality test for the effects of AI on ERU, GECON, and WIP are presented in Fig. 2.
Specifically, for AI→ERU, the test statistic exceeds the critical value during June 2020–December 2021 and March–April 2022,
indicating a time-varying Granger causality relationship between AI and ERU during these periods. This reflects the deepening
application of AI technology in financial market analysis and cross-border economic activities during these periods and its significant
