environment of a given period. Unlike the study by Zhong et al. (2024), who reported that the relationship between AI and ERU is
short-lived, this study identifies temporal variations in these two-way effects. These periods of variation correspond to the increasing
application of AI in financial market risk pricing and cross-border economic activity analysis amid the COVID-19 pandemic and
geopolitical tensions. The impact of AI development on GECON and WIP is undeniable. Abbas Khan et al. (2024) reported that AI has
the potential to significantly improve labour productivity, leading to a more efficient allocation of time and resources. This optimization
is expected to reshape industries, drive economic expansion, and ultimately improve the global economy. In this paper, the
relationships among these factors are phased rather than continuous. These periods of change coincide with key phases in the
application of AI. From a policy perspective, these results suggest that governments should increase its investment in AI infrastructure
during these key phases to amplify its driving effect on the economy.
The results of a time-varying Granger causality test of ERU on AI, GECON, and WIP are presented in Fig. 3. The test statistics for the
directions from ERU to AI, GECON, and WIP all fall below the critical value, indicating that during the sample period (2020–2023),
ERU does not exhibit a time-varying effect on AI, GECON, or WIP. This finding indicates that ERU does not have a statistically significant
time-varying causal effect on the evolution of AI technology, changes in global economic conditions, or the operation of world
industrial production. ERU does not have a statistically significant time-varying causal effect on the evolution of AI, GECON, or WIP.
Practically, these findings are meaningful for decision-making. For tech enterprises investing in AI, short-term fluctuations in energy-
related uncertainty need not be considered a direct constraint on technological R&D; for policy-makers, stabilizing the global economy
or industrial production does not require overemphasizing the direct mitigation of ERU’s impact, as its influence (if any) is likely
transmitted through indirect channels rather than direct causal links.
