The results of time-varying Granger causality tests for WIP on AI, ERU, and GECON are presented in Fig. 5. Specifically, for
WIP→AI, the test statistics are nonsignificant throughout the sample period. This may be because AI technology development is driven
more by endogenous factors such as the technological innovation cycle and digital transformation policies and has a weaker direct
correlation with short-term fluctuations in industrial production. For WIP→ERU, the test statistic exceeded the critical value during
April–October 2021. During this period, WIP was in a critical postpandemic recovery phase. The expansion of energy-intensive industries
drove up energy demand, exacerbating the imbalance between supply and demand in the energy market and significantly
increasing energy-related uncertainty. For WIP→GECON, the test statistic significantly exceeded the critical value between March
2020 and November 2023. As core components of the real sector of the global economy, the scale of world industrial production and
the performance of industrial chains directly reflect the level of global economic prosperity (Baumeister et al. 2022). The initial
production shutdowns during the pandemic, followed by subsequent recovery and structural adjustments, had a sustained and significant
effect on global economic conditions, thus forming a long-term, time-varying causal relationship. These findings demonstrate
that the impact of world industrial production on technology adoption, energy market expectations, and the global economic landscape
exhibits distinct phased and correlated characteristics.
To further verify the robustness of the results, this paper replaces the minimum estimated window size for robustness testing. The
results of the time-varying Granger causality tests are presented in Fig. 6. A comparison of the data in Figs. 2–5 clearly reveals that the
detection results in Fig. 6 are robust. Therefore, the above test results are reliable.
5. Conclusions
This paper explores the time-varying nexus between AI and financial resilience across the energy, economic, and industrial domains.
Economically, AI’s impact on financial resilience is scenario dependent and time bound. GECON, as a macro hub, drives energy
uncertainty and industrial production in the long term, while industrial production’s influence on the energy market evolves
