dynamically with the industrial cycle. These findings provide insights for policy-makers to formulate financial stability strategies and
for market participants to conduct risk management. Overall, this study contributes empirical evidence for understanding the dynamic
interaction mechanism between technological innovation and financial resilience.
Thus, policy-makers should first establish a stage-specific AI-related policy adjustment mechanism on the basis of the time-varying
characteristics of AI’s impact on financial resilience. Since AI had more significant effects on ERU, GECON, and WIP after 2020, policy-
makers should prioritize the allocation of policy resources to AI application scenarios that increase macroeconomic stability and industrial
production efficiency in the post-2020 context. Second, it can introduce targeted policy buffers for energy markets. As ERU has
no significant effect on the other indicators but is affected by AI, GECON, and WIP, policies such as energy price stabilization funds or
flexible energy supply adjustment mechanisms can be launched to mitigate the spillover effects of AI-driven technological changes and
industrial cycle fluctuations on the energy market. On the other hand, market participants should first adopt AI-driven dynamic asset
allocation strategies on the basis of the time-bound nature of AI’s impact. Since AI’s influence on financial resilience indicators
strengthened after 2020, investors can increase allocations to AI-related assets in periods when AI’s positive effects on GECON and WIP
are prominent and reduce exposures when AI’s driving role weakens. Second, they could design industrial cycle-linked risk hedging
tools while considering WIP’s dynamic impact. Given WIP’s significant influence on ERU from April to October 2021 and persistent
impact on GECON since March 2020, investors can develop futures or options products linked to WIP to hedge against energy market
uncertainty during peak industrial cycle periods and macroeconomic volatility in the long term.
